  "opinion": "As a woman in my 40s who works as a cleaner in Bari, Italy, I’ve seen firsthand how the gender gap in science affects everyone, not just those in labs or classrooms. My parents, both with PhDs, raised me to value education, but I’ve never had the chance to pursue a science degree myself—my vocational diploma is all I’ve got. I’ve noticed that in the community centers where I volunteer, women often feel invisible when they talk about their interests in science, as if it’s not ‘for them.’ This isn’t just about numbers; it’s about the quiet fear many women feel when they try to engage with science. The gap isn’t just about fewer women in STEM fields—it’s about the lack of role models who reflect their lived experiences. I’ve read that in Italy, women make up only 30% of PhDs in science, and that’s a huge number to overcome. Should we address it? Absolutely. But the way we do it matters. We need to create spaces where women feel safe to ask questions without judgment, like the mentorship programs I’ve heard about in some schools. I also think it’s important to challenge the stereotypes that say science is only for boys. When I read novels, I often find stories where women are scientists, and it helps me imagine myself in those roles. But for many women, especially those from working-class backgrounds like mine, it’s hard to see themselves reflected in science. We need to make science accessible in ways that don’t require expensive degrees or degrees that don’t match your life. It’s not just about fixing the numbers—it’s about changing the culture so that everyone feels they belong. And for me, as someone who’s anxious about speaking up, it’s about finding the courage to say, ‘I want to learn.’",
